r Commemoration in Jamaica -- t15. “Lest We Forget”: Terror and the Politics of Commemoration in Guyana -- t16. “Tortured Bodies”: The Biopolitics of Torture and Truth in Chile -- tSection Four: Thinking Humanitarianism / Thinking Terror -- t17. Introduction to Section Four -- t18. From the Northern Territory Emergency Response to Stronger Futures: Where Is the Evidence That Australian Aboriginal Women Are Leading Self-Determining Lives? -- t19. Power in/through Speaking of Terror: The Geopolitics and Anti-Politics of Discourses on Violence in Other Places -- t20. Africa, 9/11, and the Temporality and Spatiality of Race and Terror -- t21. Humanitarianism as Planetary Politics -- tSection Five: Terror Circuits -- t22. Introduction to Section Five -- t23. Visual Colonial Economies and Slave Death in Modernity: Bin Laden’s Terror? -- t24. Viewing Violence in a Far Country: Abu Ghraib and Terror’s New Performativities -- t25. Fighting Terror: Race, Sex, and the Monstrosity of Islam -- tSection Six: Theorizing (at) the Limits of Justice -- t26. Introduction to Section Six -- t27. In Terror, in Love, out of Time -- t28. Radical Praxis or Knowing (at) the Limits of Justice -- t29. Unsewing My Lips, Breathing My Voice: The Spoken and Unspoken Truth of Transnational Violence -- t30. Mori Cards: The Body Bags Installation -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fear and violence that followed the events of September 11, 2001 touched lives all around the world, even in places that few would immediately associate with the global war on terror. In At the Limits of Justice, twenty-nine contributors from six countries explore the proximity of terror in their own lives and in places ranging from Canada and the United States to Jamaica, Palestine/Israel, Australia, Guyana, Chile, Pakistan, and across the African continent.In this collection, female scholars of colour – including leading theorists on issues of indigeneity, race, and feminism – examine the political, social, and personal repercussions of the war on terror through contributions that range from testimony and poetry to scholarly analysis. Inspired by both the personal and the global impact of this violence within the war on terror, they expose the way in which the war on terror is presented as a distant and foreign issue at the same time that it is deeply present in the lives of women and others all around the world.An impassioned but rigorous examination of issues of race and gender in contemporary politics, At the Limits of Justice is also a call to create moral communities which will find terror and violence unacceptable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aTerrorismxSocial aspects. 0aViolencexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbas, Asma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgathangelou, Anna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArat-Koç, Sedef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBobis, Merlinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharania, Gulzar R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDa Silva, Denise Ferreira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord-Smith, Honor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrewal, Inderpal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJahangeer, Roshan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJamal, Amina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwak, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacias